[2
From: woodall@wadsworth.org
To respond point by point:
First, note that the official report was posted 8 days later than the
ProMED-mail report, and was reposted on ProMED-mail.
Second, when a person sends a letter to the editor of a journal or
newspaper regarding an article that was published, that person normally
hopes to see an edited version of that letter appear, unless s/he
specifically states it is not for publication. The same applies to a
moderated list like ProMED-mail.
Also, the original posting about the outbreak was NOT anonymous; the
contributor, who works for a UK health agency, requested that the name be
withheld.
Third, besides the comments quoted by Dr Weinberg, there have been
substantially more in favor of the idea that the overriding benefit to
public health comes from publication without delay (several more taking
this view, and only one more against it, have been received since the
compilation that was posted).
Fourth, there is a fine line between waiting for "the best time to put
information in the public domain" and repressing information.
Fifth, see "Third" and "Fourth" above.
Finally, I believe ProMED-mail subscribers send in information because they
think it is important for it to be disseminated. I know that the
moderators post information for that reason. Rest assured that we take our
responsibility seriously.
--
Jack Woodall, Ph.D., Director, ProMED-mail
Wadsworth Center
New York State Dept.of Health, Albany NY, USA
e-mail: woodall@wadsworth.org
http://www.fas.org/promed/
http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html
